# No redundant, duplicated, or orphaned code

When adding, reviewing, or refactoring code in this codebase, apply the following checks so Cursor AI enforces a strict standard every time.

## Definitions

- **Orphaned**: Code (file, export, or function) that is never imported or called from any live code path.
- **Duplicated**: The same responsibility or business rule implemented in more than one place.
- **Redundant**: A thin wrapper or re-export that only forwards to another module and adds no meaningful behavior (e.g. one extra call like `markForCheck()`).

## Mandatory procedure

### 1. Orphan check (for the area you are changing)

- For each **new or touched export** (file or named export), run a project-wide search for imports of that symbol or file path.
- If the only reference is the definition site, treat it as **orphaned** and either remove it or add a real consumer.
- For **barrel/re-export files**: verify that consumers import from the barrel for that symbol; if they import from the concrete file instead, the barrel’s re-export for that symbol is orphaned.

### 2. Duplicate check

- Search for the **same function name or same business rule** (e.g. "map X to Y", "validate contact name", "max length 100") in other files.
- If two or more places implement the same behavior, treat as **duplicated**; keep one source of truth and remove or delegate to it.

### 3. Redundant layer check

- For **handler/wrapper modules** that only call another module and then do one small side effect (e.g. `changeDetectorRef.markForCheck()`): treat as **redundant** unless there is a strong reason to keep the layer. Prefer inlining or a single place that does the side effect.

### 4. Chain check (only-used-by-orphan)

- If a file A is only imported by file B, and B is orphaned (never imported), then A is **orphaned as well**. Remove or replace the entire chain.

## When to run this

- **Before adding a new util/helper file**: Confirm it will be imported from at least one call site; avoid "just in case" modules.
- **When reviewing a PR or doing a code review**: Run the procedure for the changed module (or folder) and report orphans, duplicates, and redundant wrappers.
- **When refactoring a folder**: Run the full procedure for that folder and trim orphans, merge duplicates, and collapse redundant layers.

## Outcome

- **Orphaned**: Delete or wire to a real consumer.
- **Duplicated**: Single implementation; others call or delegate to it.
- **Redundant**: Remove the wrapper or merge behavior into one place.

This rule applies to all TypeScript in the repo; apply it to any module you are editing or reviewing, not only a single folder.
